          "body": "Psalm 80 opens with three stacked titles that constitute a full theological portrait of Israel's God: 'Shepherd of Israel' (the pastoral metaphor of covenant care, cf. Psalm 23:1; Genesis 48:15), 'You who lead Joseph like a flock' (the Exodus as shepherding), and 'You who are enthroned above the cherubim' (the ark-presence, 1 Samuel 4:4; 2 Samuel 6:2). The juxtaposition is striking — the same God who leads a flock is also the One enthroned in cosmic majesty between the heavenly creatures. The prayer begins by naming God's two-handed character: intimate shepherd and transcendent sovereign. The initial command 'shine forth' (*yapah*, meaning to blaze, to appear in splendor) is a theophanic request — the same God who revealed Himself in fire and cloud to Israel's ancestors must now appear again. The congregants are not asking for a new God; they are asking the same God who acted then to act now. All genuine lament begins here: with a God whose past acts are the ground of present petition."
