        "excerpt": "Oh, give ear, Shepherd of Israel, You who lead Joseph like a flock; You who are enthroned above the cherubim, shine forth!",
        "body": "The psalm opens with a five-fold invocation before making a single request, and the five titles are not decorative but argumentative. 'Shepherd of Israel' — God is the one who tends, leads, protects, and is responsible for the welfare of His flock. 'You who lead Joseph like a flock' — the Exodus is named as the paradigm act of divine shepherding; 'Joseph' here stands for the northern tribes, the sons of Jacob's beloved son. 'You who are enthroned above the cherubim' — this title connects God directly to the ark of the covenant, the visible sign of His localized presence in Israel's midst (1 Samuel 4:4; 2 Kings 19:15). The three titles together span God's character: intimate pastoral care, historical deliverance, and cosmic enthroned majesty.\n\nThe first imperative 'give ear' (*azan*) is the standard lament opening; the second 'shine forth' (*yapah*) is a theophanic command — the request for God to appear in His blazing splendor as He had appeared in fire and cloud at Sinai and in the pillar during the wilderness years. Deuteronomy 33:2 and Psalm 50:2 use similar theophanic language of God 'shining forth' in judgment; here it is pled in the direction of salvation. The congregation is asking for nothing less than a new theophany — a fresh manifestation of the God who once showed Himself unmistakably.\n\nVerse 2 narrows the request geographically and tribally: 'Before Ephraim and Benjamin and Manasseh.' These three tribes formed the western division of the wilderness camp, directly behind the ark. The prayer is that God would move again before these specific tribes as He once moved before Israel in the wilderness — the theophany-in-motion that was the cloud by day and fire by night. The military urgency of 'stir up Your power and come to save us' invokes God as the Divine Warrior whose power needs only to be 'stirred' (*ur*, to awaken, arouse) for victory to follow.\n\nThe refrain in verse 3 establishes the psalm's covenant logic: God restoring the people (*shub*, causing them to return/be restored) + God's face shining = salvation. This is not a formula but a covenant structure — the movement from wrath to favor produces the movement from ruin to rescue. John Calvin comments that this refrain 'contains the sum of all our prayers — we ask for nothing more than that God would look upon us with a favorable countenance, for if He does so, all things must necessarily go well with us.'\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yapah* (shine forth) — to blaze, to appear in splendor; a theophanic verb used of God's appearing in Deuteronomy 33:2 and Psalm 50:2. *Ur* (stir up) — to arouse, awaken; used of the Divine Warrior rousing Himself for battle (Isaiah 51:9; Psalm 44:23). *Shub* in the refrain is hiphil causative: 'cause us to return/be restored' — a gracious divine initiative, not a human achievement."
